\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 Let's back up a bit. Sometimes, it would be beneficial for a class to have two superclasses. For example, consider a board game. Clearly, a board game is a type of game. It has rules, players, and a goal. So we could have a BoardGame class that inherits from a Game class.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:33:17 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 But a board game is also a product that is sold in a store. It has a price, a weight, a seller, and a resale value, potentially. So we might also like it if BoardGame inherited from Product.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:33:40 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 Note that Game and Product are very different things. Baseball is a game, but not a product. A laptop is a product, but not a game. So we can't make one a subclass of the other.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:34:31 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 When a class has more than one superclass, we have what is known as \cf4 multiple inheritance\cf0 . Both Python and C++ have mechanisms to allow it. However, Java does not. Can you think why?
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720
