\b \cf0 It would be really nice to allow a BoardGame object, though, to be placed in both an ArrayList of Games and an ArrayList of Products. Fortunately, Java has a compromise solution.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:36:01 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 Remember one of the problems with multiple inheritance is what happens if there is code in both superclasses for the same method. But if one of the superclasses has it as an 
\i abstract
\i0  method, then there is no code in the method. No code, no conflict.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:36:22 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 To be safe, we have to ensure that none of the methods in one of the two superclasses has any code. So we can have multiple inheritance if one of the classes has entirely abstract methods. And it can't have any instance variables, since those might potentially cause a conflict as well. We call such a class an \cf4 interface\cf0 .
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:36:42 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 So, for our BoardGame example, we can define a class called Game just like we do normally. BoardGame will extend Game to get all the Game methods and instance variables.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:36:53 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 Then we could also define an interface called Product. It would consist of a bunch of abstract methods like getPrice, setPrice, sell, returnToStore, etc. We would then have BoardGame \cf4 implement\cf0  this interface. The BoardGame class would have code for each of the abstract methods in Product.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf2 dkneezel
\b0 \cf0  
\fs20 7:37:15 pm
\fs26 \
\pard\pardeftab720

\b \cf0 We can use a BoardGame object in a Game variable. We can call Game methods since BoardGame is a subclass. And we can use a BoardGame object in a Product variable, since we know BoardGame implements all the needed methods for a Product.
\b0 \
\pard\pardeftab720
