\b \cf0 The explanation is a little complex. There are actually two kinds of exceptions in Java: \cf4 unchecked\cf0  and \cf4 checked\cf0 . An unchecked exception is one that a Java program does not have to deal with. When they occur, we don't need a try-catch block to handle them. If there's no block, then the exception is passed along to the caller. If the caller doesn't handle it, the exception goes to \cf4 its\cf0  caller, and so forth. Eventually the exception reaches main, and if main doesn't deal with it, the program crashes with lots of red lines.
